snippet.textDisplay: Bryce was a horrible person, but MURDERING him makes you just as bad of a person as he was. Instead of turning this into some half baked mystery, the writers should've just had someone murder him, then followed the killer's story as they struggled to cope with their own heinous act. Watch as the character first thinks they're a hero who did the right thing and saved the day, but then they quickly realize they've done something unforgivable when that murder rips the whole school apart. Trap that character in a hellish nightmare, make them have to reflect each and every day if they're really any better than Bryce was by killing him. Make that character become slowly twisted and isolated from everybody who cares about them by the maddening guilt as the police narrow down their list of suspects one by one. Turn this murder into a tragedy that just pushes everyone to their breaking points, where Bryce is still causing everyone hell even long after he's dead.
snippet.textOriginal: Bryce was a horrible person, but MURDERING him makes you just as bad of a person as he was. Instead of turning this into some half baked mystery, the writers should've just had someone murder him, then followed the killer's story as they struggled to cope with their own heinous act. Watch as the character first thinks they're a hero who did the right thing and saved the day, but then they quickly realize they've done something unforgivable when that murder rips the whole school apart. Trap that character in a hellish nightmare, make them have to reflect each and every day if they're really any better than Bryce was by killing him. Make that character become slowly twisted and isolated from everybody who cares about them by the maddening guilt as the police narrow down their list of suspects one by one. Turn this murder into a tragedy that just pushes everyone to their breaking points, where Bryce is still causing everyone hell even long after he's dead.

snippet.textDisplay: The idea of redeeming “irredeemable” characters isn’t exactly new.  Megatron from Transformers, Endeavor from My Hero Academia, Loki from Marvel, Billy from Stranger Things, are all characters who on the surface seemed like irredeemable pieces of shit, but had their backstories set up in a way that you could hold some level of sympathy and understanding for them so that when their redemption DID come, it didn’t feel forced or contrived.  The problem isn’t that the writers tried to redeem Bryce, it’s that they never properly set out to redeem him in the first place.  If he had been set up since the first season as this “morally grey” trauamtized character, then it would make sense.  But since the very beginning, he was portrayed as this cartoonishly evil monster who had no depth beyond being a sociopath.  So the half-assed attempts to make the audience suddenly feel for him out of the blue just feels super disingenuous.
